Sure, here are some code examples of the difference between a domain service and an application service in the context of a payment instrument domain model implemented in Java:

Domain Service Example:
```java
public interface PaymentInstrumentService {
    void addPaymentInstrument(PaymentInstrument paymentInstrument);
    void removePaymentInstrument(String paymentInstrumentId);
    PaymentInstrument getPaymentInstrument(String paymentInstrumentId);
    List<PaymentInstrument> getPaymentInstrumentsByCustomerId(String customerId);
}
```
In this example, the `PaymentInstrumentService` interface is defined in the domain layer. It provides methods to add, remove, and retrieve payment instruments, and it is responsible for enforcing domain-specific business rules, such as ensuring that each payment instrument has a unique identifier and belongs to a valid customer. The implementation of this service is also done in the domain layer.

Application Service Example:
```typescript
@Service
@Transactional
public class PaymentInstrumentApplicationService {
    private final PaymentInstrumentService paymentInstrumentService;
    private final CustomerService customerService;

    public PaymentInstrumentApplicationService(PaymentInstrumentService paymentInstrumentService, CustomerService customerService) {
        this.paymentInstrumentService = paymentInstrumentService;
        this.customerService = customerService;
    }

    public void addPaymentInstrument(String customerId, PaymentInstrumentDto paymentInstrumentDto) {
        Customer customer = customerService.getCustomer(customerId);
        PaymentInstrument paymentInstrument = PaymentInstrument.from(paymentInstrumentDto, customer);
        paymentInstrumentService.addPaymentInstrument(paymentInstrument);
    }

    public void removePaymentInstrument(String paymentInstrumentId) {
        paymentInstrumentService.removePaymentInstrument(paymentInstrumentId);
    }

    public PaymentInstrumentDto getPaymentInstrument(String paymentInstrumentId) {
        PaymentInstrument paymentInstrument = paymentInstrumentService.getPaymentInstrument(paymentInstrumentId);
        return PaymentInstrumentDto.from(paymentInstrument);
    }

    public List<PaymentInstrumentDto> getPaymentInstrumentsByCustomerId(String customerId) {
        List<PaymentInstrument> paymentInstruments = paymentInstrumentService.getPaymentInstrumentsByCustomerId(customerId);
        return paymentInstruments.stream().map(PaymentInstrumentDto::from).collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}
```
In this example, the `PaymentInstrumentApplicationService` class is defined in the application layer. It uses the `PaymentInstrumentService` interface and the `CustomerService` interface to implement the use cases of adding, removing, and retrieving payment instruments. The `PaymentInstrumentApplicationService` is responsible for orchestrating the domain logic to accomplish the use cases. It also handles application-specific concerns, such as mapping between DTOs and domain objects, and wrapping the use cases in a transactional boundary.

In summary, the domain service provides an interface for the domain layer to implement the business logic of a specific domain model, while the application service is responsible for orchestrating the domain logic to accomplish the use cases of the application, and handles application-specific concerns.
